35 people were kidnapped by Mayi Mayi Simba militiamen in the Mambaka locality, close to Biakatu.

ACTOR2: FRPI: Front for Patriotic Resistance of Ituri
NOTES: 4 FRPI militiamen were killed in a clash with FARDC soldiers in the Burasi locality. The military returned 68 cows the militia had stolen to citizens of the area.

ALLY_ACTOR_2: Nande Ethnic Group (Democratic Republic of Congo)
NOTES: Angry residents of the Biakato area killed a person and burned some houses of Yira (a subset of the Nande ethnic group) members of the community after a traditional leader was killed.

NOTES: A traditional leader was reportedly assassinated in the Biakato area, leading to violence by local residents.

ACTOR2: Police Guards of Virunga National Park
NOTES: Suspected LRA gunmen attacked park rangers in the Karuruma area of the Virunga National Park. The rangers managed to repulse the attackers, killing one. The LRA has been known to engage in poaching in the area and to conduct attacks against park rangers.

ACTOR1: Unidentified Armed Group (Democratic Republic of Congo)
NOTES: Government forces have forced "local and foreign armed groups" to retreat from the Miriki area. These militias have moved towards the towns of Kamandi and Bunyatenge.

Around 5,000 people protested in Bukavu to demand the holding of presidential elections in 2016.
A coalition of opposition political parties held demonstrations in Goma to commemorate those who died in marches against the revision of the electoral laws in January 2015.

ALLY_ACTOR_1: Military Forces of Democratic Republic of Congo (2001-)
SOURCE: Agence France Presse; Radio Okapi; Radio France Internationale

NOTES: A G7 demonstration to demand presidential elections in 2016 were prevented by police in Kinshasa. About 100 people were arrested (this number also includes the Lubumbashi demonstration which was disrupted).
Nursing staff of medical training institues launched an indefinite strike with minimum service.

ACTOR1: Military Forces of Democratic Republic of Congo (2001-) National Intelligence Agency
NOTES: The leader of the G7 opposition coalition was detained by agents of the National Intelligence Agency in Lubumbashi as he was on his way to his "stronghold" in Kalemie.

ACTOR1: FDLR: Democratic Forces for the Liberation of Rwanda
NOTES: 3 people were killed and 4 injured in an attack by the FDLR on Virira village in Lubero territory, about 40km away from Miriki.

ALLY_ACTOR_2: Nande Ethnic Group (Democratic Republic of Congo)
NOTES: 8 local leaders of the Nande community in Nyamilima were arrested on suspicion of setting fire to the home of a local MP. The arrests have led to tensions between the Nande and Hutu communities in the area.

ACTOR1: ADF-NALU: Allied Democratic Forces-National Army for the Liberation of Uganda
NOTES: A young man who escaped ADF kidnappers reported that a group of people were taken in Beni territory and transported to a location near Oicha. At least 5 were killed after chosing not to join the rebel group.
Mayi Mayi militiamen looted livestock from areas along the Yalingo-Yomayi axis in the Opala area.
Parents and teachers demonstrated in several cities in South Kivu to protest against the treatment of teachers by parents in schools.

ACTOR1: Police Forces of Democratic Republic of Congo (2001-)
NOTES: Police killed a human rights activist and seriously injured 3 others during a demonstration against the Banro mining company's failure to fulfill its commitments to the local community.

ACTOR1: FDLR-RUD: Democratic Forces for the Liberation of Rwanda-Rally for Unity and Democracy
NOTES: FDLR rebels allegedly kidnapped 50 families and burned their homes in the Bushalingwa locality of the Ikobo group, which straddles the Lubero and Walikale territories.
Employees of the Provincial Divison of Mines observed a work stoppage to demand the departure of their Head of Divison whom they accuse of mismanagement.

ACTOR1: MONUSCO: United Nations Organization Stabilization Mission in Democratic Republic of Congo (2010-)
NOTES: MONUSCO has deployed additional troops to the Alimba area, specifically focusing on the DRC's border with Burundi.
Students from various universities from the former Kasai Oriental province protested against the closing of their institutes in Mbuji Mayi.

ACTOR1: FDLR: Democratic Forces for the Liberation of Rwanda
ACTOR2: FDLR: Democratic Forces for the Liberation of Rwanda
NOTES: FARDC soldiers have dislodged FDLR rebels from several localities of Walikale and Lubero, including Buleusa, Rusamambo, Mizinga, Rusoha and others as of Jan.31. At least 2 FLDR officers were killed, while weapons and combatants were captured during the operations.

At least 6 people were kidnapped by Raia Mutmomboki militiamen as they were on their way to a seminar on sexual violence in Lulingu. They were later ransomed.

ACTOR2: Police Forces of Democratic Republic of Congo (2001-)
NOTES: 3 people were killed, including 2 police, and 3 others injured when unidentified gunmen attacked a police station in Karuba, Kalangala group, North Kivu.
The head of the Gaya chiefdom of Bondo claimed that LRA rebels set up a training camp with new recruits in the abandoned towns of Mabia 1 and 2.
4 people were kidnapped by Raia Mutomboki militiamen in the mining town of Nduma.

Kadar Abdi Ibrahim, publication co-director of the Aurore newspaper, was arrested by police in connection with the publication of a photograph of a seven-year-old girl who died during the violent dispersal of a religious ceremony by the police and the Djibouti army on 21 December 2015. He was reportedly tortured in detention. He was later condemned to a two-month suspended prison sentence, while the publication of this monthly newspaper was also suspended for two months.

Cairo, Jan 2 (MENA) - Military spokesman Muhammad Samir said on Saturday [2 January] that a cache containing explosives and artillery had been detected and seized on Mount Um Hasirah near al-Qusaymah area in Central Sinai. Thirty-two sacks of highly-explosive TNT have been found inside the cache.

SOURCE: Aswat Masriya; Al-Masry Al-Youm; Xinhua General News Service
NOTES: The Egyptian military announced the killing of 29 Islamist elements in North Sinai on 3 January as part of the implementation of the "Matry's Right" operation in the towns of Arish, Rafah and Sheikh Zuweid.

SOURCE: Aswat Masriya; Al-Masry Al-Youm; Daily News Egypt; Xinhua General News Service
NOTES: Security forces based in North Sinai killed a total of 32 militants and arrested four suspects in an exchange of fire in Arish, Rafah and Sheikh Zuweid. 32 fatalities recorded over 3 events [10 in Al-Arish; 10 in Rafah and 9 in Sheikh Zuweyid].
An Egyptian solider and civilian were injured in a bomb attack in Al-Arish City, North Sinai when a roadside bomb detonated on 4 January.

Dozens stood in solidarity with Al-Azhar critic Islam El-Beheiry on one of his appeal trial sessions at the Zeinhom court on 4 January. Protesters denounced his trial as they carried signs describing Al-Azhar as the "prison of enlightened thought", while others said "Islam did not despise the Quran or Islam".

SOURCE: Aswat Masriya; Al-Masry Al-Youm; Daily News Egypt; Xinhua General News Service
NOTES: Security forces based in North Sinai killed a total of 32 militants and arrested four suspects in an exchange of fire in Arish, Rafah and Sheikh Zuweid. 32 fatalities recorded over 3 events [10 in Al-Arish; 10 in Rafah and 9 in Sheikh Zuweyid].

SOURCE: Aswat Masriya; Daily News Egypt; MENA news agency
NOTES: Unidentified assailants shot dead a police officer in the Upper Egypt province of Beni Suef as he was on his way home. A citizen was also injured in the incident as he was crossing the site of the shooting to get to his car. No militant group has declared responsibility for the attack yet.

Dozens of reward preachers in the Ministry of Religious Endowments who work without permanent contracts and the attendant financial security protested on 5 January in front of the Press Syndicate, demanding to be permanently hired.
Egyptian army forces killed 11 Islamist militants and arrested two suspects in the context of the "Martyr's Right" military operation in northern and central areas in Sinai.

At least 14 Islamist militants were killed and 13 others arrested by the Egyptian Armed Forces in the North Sinai province. Operations were conducted in North Sinai's Arish, Sheikh Zuweid and Rafah cities. The forces also managed to dismantle 16 explosive devices that have been planted on the roads to target security men. Fatalities divided between three events (5 fatalities recorded in Al Arish, 5 in Rafah and 4 in Sheikh Zuweyid).

SOURCE: Agence France Presse; Associated Press International; Xinhua General News Service
NOTES: The Egyptian branch of the Islamic State group blew up a gas pipeline that supplies the northern Sinai city of Al-Arish city and a nearby industrial military complex. Explosives were used to target the pipeline in the Al-Midan area, about 15 km from the entrance of Arish city.

SOURCE: Agence France Presse; Associated Press International
NOTES: A gang of around 15 people hurled fireworks and fired birdshot at police guarding a hotel in Giza's Haram district on 7 January where Arab Israelis were staying without hurting anyone. Unknown assailants had gathered outside the hotel and carried out the attack, which it said targeted police guarding the hotel, who fired back. Associated Press International reported that an Egyptian Islamic State affiliate claimed responsibility for an attack on the hotel near the Giza Pyramids, and that after throwing Molotov cocktails, the attackers "started firing at the hotel with live bullets."

At least 14 Islamist militants were killed and 13 others arrested by the Egyptian Armed Forces in the North Sinai province. Operations were conducted in North Sinai's Arish, Sheikh Zuweid and Rafah cities. The forces also managed to dismantle 16 explosive devices that have been planted on the roads to target security men. Fatalities divided between three events (5 fatalities recorded in Al Arish, 5 in Rafah and 4 in Sheikh Zuweyid).

At least 14 Islamist militants were killed and 13 others arrested by the Egyptian Armed Forces in the North Sinai province. Operations were conducted in North Sinai's Arish, Sheikh Zuweid and Rafah cities. The forces also managed to dismantle 16 explosive devices that have been planted on the roads to target security men. Fatalities divided between three events (5 fatalities recorded in Al Arish, 5 in Rafah and 4 in Sheikh Zuweyid).

The police killed three militants in Sharqiya province north of the capital Cairo during fire exchange while arresting them for an attempted assassination of a university official. Investigations showed that the three militants were two college students and an electrician in their late 20s and 30s, who failed to gun down a university official in December .
One of the assailants of a knife attack on a hotel in Hurghada was killed and the other seriously wounded, a police official said earlier, adding that security forces had "foiled" the attack.

SOURCE: Agence France Presse; Associated Press Online
NOTES: Two Austrian and one Swedish tourist suffered knife wounds when unknown assailants attacked a hotel in Hurghada. A police official said security forces stopped the attack on the Bella Vista hotel in the Red Sea resort of Hurghada, with one assailant killed and another "seriously wounded". No one has so far claimed responsibility for the attack in Hurghada.

In Hurghada, a student, reported to have participated in the attack on the Bella Vista Resort on Friday night was reported to have been a victim of enforced disappearance. He was killed by security forces after the attack. This is contrary to the state-sanctioned disclosure.

Chairman of the Egyptian Commission for Rights and Freedoms (ECRF) Ahmed Abdullah was allegedly the subject of an attempted act of "kidnapping" by security forces on Saturday. Three men in civilian clothes claiming to belong to the police forces raided the coffee shop often visited by Abdullah in the Agouza district but he was not present.

The Muslim Brotherhood accused the Egyptian security forces of "assassinating" a gynecologist in an extrajudicial killing as they were arresting him in Fayoum as he was leaving his private clinic on 9 January.

Armed assailants shot a dead police colonel and a conscript in Egypt's Giza. The ISIS-affiliated group "Sinai Province" claimed responsibility for the attack later on Saturday in a statement posted on an affiliated twitter account.

On Jan. 9, the Monib Traffic Department Director and a conscript were killed after their vehicle was attacked by anonymous gunmen in Giza. The attack was claimed by the ISIS-affiliated group Sinai Province.

Armed assailants affiliated with the "Islamic State" (IS) attacked a compound owned by a cleaning company called Care Service in Al-Arish, North Sinai on 10 January. They set the compound on fire; however no injuries were reported among the company's workers. Eyewitnesses said the attackers evacuated all 125 employees from their dormitories before setting it ablaze, causing at least 40 vehicles owned by the authority to catch fire and a string of explosions in the area. One worker said he and other colleagues were not wounded, but revealed that the assailants, after checking the employees IDs, threatened them with death if they cooperate with security again.

A man in Beni Sueif was killed after he was forcibly disappeared on 10 January without knowing the charges against him. However, the Ministry of Interior later announced that their forces killed him in an exchange of fire on a farm.
Hundreds of participants gathered for the prayer and chanted denouncements of the government at the funeral of a doctor killed by policemen on 10 January in Fayoum.

There was an explosion on 12 January on Al-Ayatt railway track in the Giza Governorate. No causalities were reported in the blast. Two additional explosive devices were found on the railway track in front of Mansha Fadel in the town of Al-Ayatt. Explosives experts defused them.

The student union at Cairo Universitys Faculty of Arts said on 13 January they were staging a protest to denounce the death of a colleague, who died following a heart attack, after an observer kicked her out of her exam.
Two security recruits and a civilian were wounded on 14 January as a blast targeted a security patrol at the coastal road in the area between Arish and Sheikh Zuweid cities.
A bomb disposal team defused an improvised explosive device planted near a school and a power transformer in Arish city.

North Sinai security forces killed 30 militants and injured 10 as militant elements attempted to attack a military ambush in south Sheikh Zuweid. The attack resulted in the death of four military personnel and the injury of eight others.
A primitive bomb exploded behind a closed traffic police unit on the Ring Road in Giza with no casualties reported.

A police officer, two conscripts and two civilians were injured on 19 January as a bomb went off near Al-Maydan checkpoint near North Sinai's capital city Arish.  A roadside bomb went off as a military vehicle was passing by. The Islamic State-affiliated State  of Sinai group claimed responsibility on Twitter.

SOURCE: Xinhua General News Service; Ahram; Agence France Presse; Egypt Independent
NOTES: Between five and seven Egyptian policemen were killed on 20 January in an armed attack in Egypt's North Sinai city of Arish. Militants attacked security forces at Atlawy Square in Arish, killing five policemen and injuring 10 others. The Islamic State group's Egyptian affiliate, the Sinai Province, claimed that attack.

A young Egyptian man, was found dead on 31 January after having been reported missing for two weeks. He was arrested on 20 January from his house located in the Fifth Settlement suburb in Greater Cairo. His family were not informed of where he would be detained. Friends suspect that Galal was shot immediately after he went missing, and that his body may have been at the morgue for the entire ten days.

SOURCE: Agence France Presse; Aswat Masriya; Xinhua General News Service; Egypt Independent
NOTES: A bomb blast killed eleven people, including eight Egyptian policemen and three civilians, as a team of officers on 21 January raided an apartment in Al-Haram district suspected to be a militant hideout.The interior ministry blamed Thursday's incident on the blacklisted Islamist Muslim Brotherhood movement of ousted president Mohamed Morsi. However, Egypt Independent reported that both ISIS-affiliate group 'State of Sinai', and the 'Revolutionary Punishment' groups claimed responsibility for the attack.

Two policemen were wounded by gunfire when unknown elements opened fire at them in a village in Al-Sharqiyah Governorate [east of Cairo]. The two policemen were targeted by motorcyclists at Al-Qaramus village of Abu-Kabir city.

A missile killed one child and injured three people, after it hit their home in the Rafah city of Northern Sinai on Friday. Unknown assailiants "fired a mortar shell at a security point in Rafah but it fell on the house by mistake.

Police forces broke up three marches by Muslim Brotherhood supporters in the Berket al-Sabe', Tala and Ashmun localities, Monufiya on Friday. Protesters raised banners against President Abdel Fattah al-Sisi and others that read " Where are bread and freedom?", referring to the January 25 revolution slogan "Bread, freedom and social justice".

Protesters raised banners against President Abdel Fattah al-Sisi and others that read " Where are bread and freedom?", referring to the January 25 revolution slogan "Bread, freedom and social justice".

An attack on a checkpoint in a village in Egypt's northern Sharqiya province left two policemen and a passerby dead on 24 January. The attack also left four people injured after unidentified assailants on two motorbikes shot at the checkpoint near the town of Fakous.

SOURCE: Aswat Masriya; MENA news agency; Daily News Egypt
NOTES: The Ministry of Interior said in a statement that it raided an apartment suspected to contain explosives in Kerdasa, and was caught in an "exchange of fire" with a member of the Muslim Brotherhood in the apartment, before shooting him.
Bomb disposal teams defused a high-explosive bomb that was planted by unidentified men under an armoured cash transport car in Wabur al-Miah district.

SOURCE: Aswat Masriya; Associated Press International; MENA news agency
NOTES: In the October 6 suburb of Cairo, police killed two suspected militants in a raid. Explosives and firearms were found in the raided apartment. The suspects opened fire at the security forces upon their arrival before the forces started to shoot back.

A protest was reported in 6 of October city, on the outskirts of Giza. Dozens demonstrated near Vodafone Square, denouncing the government and the police. They also raised posters of ousted Islamist president Mohamed Morsi. However, riot police dispersed the gathering within 30 minutes of its formation.

A number of protests were reported in Sharqeya, Fayoum, Menufiya and other governorates. Most demonstrations saw protesters lining residential streets or marching through populated neighborhoods. Some  demonstrators set off fireworks before being dispersed by riot police.
Supporters of the Muslim Brotherhood movement tried to demonstrate in Cairo's Al-Haram district near the pyramids, but quickly dispersed fearing police retaliation.
Anti-riot police forces dispersed a Muslim Brotherhood protest near Mataryia Square, with protestors reporting that police used live ammunition.

SOURCE: Associated Press International; Daily News Egypt
NOTES: In Alexandria, police arrested 15 people when they dispersed small protests by Muslim Brotherhood loyalists. A total of four active demonstrations were reported in Alexandria, composed mostly of women. It was reported that the protesters carried antigovernment banners and posters depicting the the Rabaa Al-Adaweya sign.
An improvised explosive device (IED) was disarmed in Alexandria Monday morning after civilians reported a suspicious object in Al-Max Street.
Dozens of supporters of the Muslim Brotherhood blocked a main road in Bahtim, Qalyubiya on 25 January, burning car tires before fleeing away.
Minor protests reportedly erupted in Bani Suaif and other provinces.

SOURCE: Associated Press International; MENA news agency
NOTES: in Bani Suef province south of Cairo, police shot and killed a suspected militant when he tried to storm a checkpoint.
In Kafr El-Shiekh, eyewitnesses said police forces fired tear gas at protesters, after an attempt to block the international road in the city using burned tires.

A number of protests were reported in Sharqeya, Fayoum, Menufiya and other governorates. Most demonstrations saw protesters lining residential streets or marching through populated neighborhoods. Some  demonstrators set off fireworks before being dispersed by riot police.
In Shubra, three protesters were arrested after setting off fireworks and blocking roads.

According to state news agency MENA, dozens of pro-government protesters marched through Tahrir Square and down Mohamed Mahmoud Street holding Egyptian flags and posters bearing the images of police victims, and chanting "The police and the people are one hand".  Security forces and military tanks were close-at-hand.

A number of protests were reported in Sharqeya, Fayoum, Menufiya and other governorates. Most demonstrations saw protesters lining residential streets or marching through populated neighborhood. Some demonstrators set off fireworks before being dispersed by riot police.
A prisoner in the city of Sharqeya died in detention at Abu Hamad police station on 26 January, two days after his arrest, amid claims by his family that he was tortured.
Security forces detonated two bombs planted near a main road west of Arish, North Sinai on 26 January. Eyewitnesses said the forces shot at the IEDs from a distance. The operation left no casualties.

One restaurant worker was mildly wounded when an IED exploded outside a court in Monufiya on 26 January. an IED planted opposite a district court in the city of Minuf caused the collapse of a primary school wall and two balconies from a nearby building. Four parked vehicles were destroyed as well.

SOURCE: Agence France Presse; Associated Press International; Daily News Egypt
NOTES: A roadside bomb hit an armored personnel carrier south of Al-Arish in the Sinai Peninsula, killing an army colonel and four soldiers and wounding twelve others. IS affiliate the Sinai Province said its members used explosive devices to target the army west of El-Arish.

An air raid reportedly killed 20 militants and wounded 15 others on 27 January at their hideouts near Arish International Airport while a massive militant cell was moving from southern Arish northwards to carry out activities.

The army shot and killed Attallah Abu Reteima, whom the sources identified as the person in charge of logistics for the Sinai Province group. The exchange of fire took place in a mountainous area in central Sinai.
Anti-government protesters in the village of Faqous, denounced the death of a prisoner in Abu Hamad police station, chanting against the police force.

SOURCE: Associated Press International; Xinhua General News Service; Aswat Masriya
NOTES: At least three policemen were killed and five others wounded on 28 January in a massive blast in a city in Egypt's North Sinai province.The blast was caused by an improvised device targeting a police armored vehicle on a main road in downtown Al-Arish. State of Sinai later claimed responsibility.
Police in Matariya hospital assaulted two doctors after they attempted to provide one of them with healthcare.

Fighting between army troops and militants in the northeastern part of the Sinai Peninsula killed four children and wounded eight other minors on 28 January. The Rafah hospital said in a statement that the children were killed and wounded during clashes using heavy weapons, with some buried under rubble when buildings were hit and collapsed. The fighting took place close to the border with the Palestinian Gaza Strip.

Dozens of Brotherhood loyalists took to the streets of Abu Hammad city of Sharqiya, 80 km north the Capital Cairo, to protest against the police. At least four people were injured by birdshots fired by Muslim Brotherhood protesters. Local shopkeepers were provoked and started confrontations, and the Brotherhood responded by firing birdshots.

A bomb blast killed two Egyptian police officers and wounded five others in an attack on their armoured vehicle in the Sinai Peninsula on 29 January. The vehicle was targeted near a school in the North Sinai provincial capital of El-Arish.
Two police conscripts were killed and two others injured after a roadside bomb exploded near an armoured police vehicle on 31 January in south Rafah in North Sinai.
An army officer and a soldier were killed in a remotely-detonated bomb attack in the Sheikh Zuweyid region of northern Sinai on 31 January. There was no immediate claim of responsibility.
Unidentified assailants set ablaze the houses of two police officers in Arish using Molotov cocktails on 31 January. There were no casualties since both houses were empty.
A 17-year-old Coptic girl was kidnapped by two men riding a tuc-tuc on 31 January in the village of Hassan Basha in Samalout, Minya.
Soldiers throwed hand grenades at protesting students at Dilla university, killing five over two days
Protests against the government's master plan at Lagahare Scondary school in Dire Dawa were met by violent response from police forces. Several students were arrested
Health professionals protested at Jimma University against the government's master plan and were met by violent response from police forces
Youth in Nekemte protested against the government's master plan and were met by violent response from police forces
Students at Shambu Prep School staged sit-ins in the school compound to protested the government's master plan and were met by violent response from police forces
Students and other people protested in Sibu Sire against the government's master plan and were met by violent response from police forces

On 2 January 2016, the OLA special unit took an ultimate action against a Woyane official in Dhengago area, East Hararghe Zone, killing him.
Farmers,businessmen, towns residents and youth marched in Hirna town, West Hararge, to protest against the government's master plan and were met by violent response from police forces
Students protested against the government's master plan in Shashamane and were met by violent response from police forces
Students protested against the government's master plan at Amba university Waliso campus on 3 January and were met by police forces
Soldiers allegedly arrested around 20 students at Dilla university who demanded to go home. The military had been preventing them from boarding buses to go home following a fire on the campus.

Farmers, businessmen, towns residents and youth marched in Hirna town, West Hararge, to protest against the government's master plan on 2 and 3 January and were met by police forces. People also protested in Rakatafura village in Tulo district on 3 January.
People protested against the government's master plan in Hidabu Abote on 4 January and were met by police forces
People protested against the government's master plan in Deder, East Harerghe, on 4 January and were met by police forces
People protested against the government's master plan in Kobbo, East Wellega on 4 January and were met by police forces
People protested against the government's master plan in Mugi town  on 4 January and were met by police forces
Soldiers allegedly attacked Adama University students on 4 January following protests against the government's master plan
Security forces allegedly arrested and killed a student at Wollega university in Nekemt on 4 January in connection with the protests against the government's master plan
People in Chiro protested against the government's master plan on 5 January and were met by police forces during West Hararge Sports Championship
Students in Awaday  school protested against the government's master plan and violent repression of protests
People in Garba Guracha (Salale/North Shawa) protested against the government's master plan on 5 January and were met by police forces
One person killed and two wounded in people protests against the government's master plan in Masala on 5 January
OFC candidate for MP Masarat Dhaba was arrested by soldiers at Qellam Wallaga high Court
People in Robe (Bale) protested against the government's master plan on 6 January and were met by police forces
Students in Chari Jarso school, Sibu Siree District protested against the government's master plan on 5 January and were met by police forces
On 5 January 2016, the Oromo Liberation Armyngaged government soldiers in a battle, putting more than 13 enemy soldiers out of action. 8 soldiers were killed.
People protested against the government's master plan in Hidabu Abote on 6 January and were met by police forces
Students in Dadar ( East Hararge)  protested against the government's master plan on 6 January. Military forces intervened.
People protested against the government's master plan in Ejere town, Salale  on 6 January and were met by police forces

People of Hirna set up road blocks on the road from Addis Ababa to Dire Dawa  on 6 January to protect themselves from the army advancing on the town from both directions. Heavy gunfire ensued when they were met by soldiers. Several people were injured and reports suggest at least 2 people were killed.
Students in Adama protested against the government's master plan and violent repression of protests. They were met by police forces. At least one student was arrested
Students protested at Lucy Secondary and Preparatory School in Shashemene. They were met by police forces
A march took place in Matahara town, Fantale District ( East Shawa). Farmers and pastoralists marched into town and were joined by students and residents.
A protest was reportedly underway in Asabot. Farmers came marching were joined by towns residents. Reportedly, heavily armed TPLF soldiers attacked these peaceful protesters.
An Oromo Protests? took place in Badessa town, West Hararge.
A protest took place at Mekele university, apparently caused by conflict between South Sudanese students and those from Gambella.
An Oromo Protest took place in Sakina town, Daro Labu ( West Hararge) Jan. 8, 2016
A Protest occurred the Hawshoo elementary school, Sinana District, Bale
A man who was supposed to get married was shot  by TPLF's outside Meta. Several others were injured.
On 8 January 2016, the Ogaden National Liberation Army ambushed a convoy carrying Abdi Mohamud Omar [president of Somali Regional State], destroying two vehicles and killing seven people
Students at Haromaya University Techno Campus defy heavy military presence to Say No to TPLF's rule by mass killing and mass eviction
Protests have reportedly taken place in Goro Re'e town, Masala District ( West Hararge).
Protests kicked off for a third round at the Madda Walabu University. Soldiers apparently have engaged students, detaining hundreds and firing live ammunition.

A protest is underway at the Haromaya University. Soldiers in the area are reportedly breaking into dormitories assaulting students.At least 3 students said to have been killed following overnight assault on Haromaya University student dormitories.
A new round of protests erupted at Jimma University Kitto Furdisa campus. During the protest 30 people were injured when a grenade was thrown at them by unidentified assailents.
Protests at the Madda Walabu University resulted in two students being  killed when soldiers fired on students.

There has been clash between TPLF forces and farmers of Jahi village located near Haromaya University. When the soldiers began firing some students escaped and ran into the villages. Soldiers pursued them clashing with farmers which were trying to protect the students
A protest is underway at Wachu Village, in the Chiro district.
A protest is underway at in Kora town, Miesso district (West Hararge).
Ambo University students resumed their protest. They chanted slogans all night long.
On 11 January, OLA forces attacked government soldiers in Gola Hurri, El Kere District, Bale Zone, killing four and wounding a number of others. Military material was also captured in the process.
A Protests? is underway at Dire Dawa University. Ethiopian authorities have cut off electricity to campus.
A massive protest is occuring at Ambo University
A protest is underway at the Jimma University.
A protest is underway at the Dire Dawa University.
In another event, 2 people were shot by soldiers near Haromaya University this morning.
Two farmers were shot by TPLF soldiers near Haromaya University department of veterinary medicine in a location called Mudde. In perhaps the same incident, one of the farmers died.
Shashemene Preparatory school students continue with their protest. Earlier they marched to the town
Protests continues in Fincha town, Abay Choman district ( Horo Guduru ).
A Protests is underway in Kofale ( west Arsi), regular army soldiers have arrived but there are no reports of violence.
A protest was underway in Wachu village.
A protest is underway in Agarfa ( Bale). The military has responded by firing on students. Several causalities feared.

Pictures show soldiers kicking student in the head at the Dadar High School ( East Hararge). Students reportedly staged peaceful silent walk through the campus. Soldiers then came, gathered them in the field and began beating them
A protest took place at the Lucy Secondary School, Shashamene ( West Arsi)
Students stage a protest at the Chercher school in Chiro.
Protesters took to the streets in Inchini Preparatory School students in Ada Barga district, West Shawa

A protest took place in Badano ( East Hararge). Students staging silent protest holsing their heads up were attached. So far 17 arrests are reported and a businessman who lifted up an injured student was badly beaten and taken to jail. January 15, 2016
Protests occurred in Shanan town, Jibat district (West Shawa). Students marched from school to the town. Federal police fired on them injuring several who being treated at clinic right now
A video shows students being beaten by government soldiers.
A protest took place at Homii Village in Abay Choman district of Horo Guduru Walaga Province.
On 16th January, farmers marched to Miesso Town in Protests as part of ongoing protests and violence
Protests have reportedly re-erupted in Ambo University Awaro Campus
Protests have erupted in Asabot town West Hararge. Farmers from the region have moved to the city condemning the killing in neighboring Miesso town
Soldiers are reportedly 'terrorizing' people in Awaday. Details of the event of scarce.
Protests are allegadly continuing in the town of Miesso. TPLF soldiers have reportedly killed two people and wounded three.
Over night, protest has began once again at Asabot town on January 18, 2016.

Reports that TPLF continues to deploy the Somali region militia known as Liyu police to attack Oromo towns and villages on the boarder. They attacked in the direction of Chinaksen in eastern Hararge killing two people.
OLA forces attacked government soldiers in a place known as Kase Hija in Gemechis District, West Hararghe Zone, killing six soldiers, wounding four, and capturing military material.
Protests have taken place in North Shawa, Dagam district, yhaya Haro village, where farmers have been protesting since the 19th January
A protest took place in Waheel town near Dirre Dawa today on January 19, 2016
A protest appears to have taken place at the Nekemt primary school. Gun fire could be hear but those responsible are unknown and little information is given.
Protests continues in Miesso, West Hararge. The regime has deployed Somalia region militia, Liyu Police killing at least 4 people so far.
On 19 January, OLA forces attacked government soldiers in Gebel Jimata, Boneya Boshe District, killing 12.
Protests in Finfinne were held around the African Union buildings.
Protests reportedly took place in Asabot (West Hararge) as Timket celebrations in Asabot turned into opportunity for protest.
Protests have taken place in North Shawa, Dagam district, yhaya Haro village, where farmers have been protesting since the 19th January
Protests took place in Kokasa, Oromia.
Oromia protests have continued in the town of Miesso.

On 20 January, Oromo citizens razed the house of a spy to the ground in Boneya Boshe District. The man used to gather intelligence for the TPLF [Tigrayan People's Liberation Front, the dominant party in the ruling coalition] forces.
OLA forces operating in Haro Limu District, western Oromia, attacked government soldiers in Abba Moa. An unknown number of soldiers died.
Protests in Finfinne were held around the African Union buildings.
A Timket protest took place in Ambo in Oromia.
Protests have taken place in North Shawa, Dagam district, yhaya Haro village, where farmers have been protesting for the last three days.
Protest took place in Bedesa during Timket festivities.
Protesters are celebrating Timket with protests in Dadar East Hararge.
Protest took place in Nekemt during Timket festivities.
A protest took place at the Birbirsa elemtary school students in Shashemene.
A protest occurred during Timket celebrations in Tulu Milki, Salale (North Shawa).
Protests continue in Asabot (West Hararge). People marched through the town. Federal police and soldiers have fired on them, killing two and wounding several.
11 students have been injured when soldiers attacked Walaga University students in Naqamte

A battle took place between farmers and local militia on one side and the military forces on the other. Two farmers and three soldiers were killed. Also 4 soldiers and several farmers sustained injuries.
Protests have continued in Jarso town, West Walaga.
Reports that soldiers continue to harass civilians. The soldiers shot and injured 3 young men in this latest violence.

Political prisoners at Maikelawi detention centre in connection with the Oromia protests began a hunger strike to protest against their denial of access to legal counsel and family visitation; their being subjected to inhuman and degrading treatment including torture, and lack of proper medical care
In Wadessa near Ambo (West Shawa), reports that soldiers have beaten young men singing during Timket celebration. At least one was killed and around 60 arrested.
Military forces allegedly killed a farmer in Wajija village near Asabot (West Hararge) on 23 January
Oromo people protested in Bordode town. Heavy military response was reported.
Students at Walaga university in Nekemt protested against the  Government's master plan. They were met by violent repression from soldiers on the campus.
People protested in East Walaga, Digga district, Arjo Gudetu village. Ethiopian soldiers fired on protesters, wounding at least three. One of them later died of his wounds.
Oromo people protested in Gurawa town, East Hararge
OLA forces attacked government soldiers in Dhomal in Habro district, killing eight soldiers and wounding another seven.
Students protested at Biftu Secondary school in Nekemt
Students at Charchar Prep School in Chiro (West Hararge) boycotted class and instead marched to hospital to visit their wounded classmates
Protests and repression by soldiers continue in Nekemt
People protested in Guji zone, Goro Dola district, Harqallo town, calling for the release of political prisoners, and against Al Amudin's Gold mining in Shakiso, Sakaro and Okkote.
People protested in Shararo town (North Shawa). 40 people were arrested and taken away by soldiers following the protests
People protested in Goro Muxi town, Metta district.
People protested in Guliso.

Students at Walaga university in Nekemt protested against the  Government's master plan. They were met by violent repression from soldiers on the campus. Several students were injured and rest are chased out of campus into the adjacent forest.
Over 20 people were killed in clashes between the Nuer and Anuak communities in Gambela Regional State over 28-30 January.
At least seven people were killed in a fierce clash between the Nuer and Anuak ethnic groups leading to an attempted prison break in Gambella town on 29 January. Scores were also left wounded.
People protested in Gidami.
OLA forces attacked government soldiers in Ija Lola in Fadis District, East Hararghe Zone, killing three soldiers and forcing the rest to retreat.
Ethiopian soldiers allegedly beat up Oromo students in Sululta town near Addis Ababa.

OLA forces attacked government soldiers at an army base named Hatura, located near Boke Tiko town in Boke district, killing 11 soldiers and wounding another 17. Military material was also captured in the attack
A special OLA forces unit killed a government soldier in East Hararghe Zone's Dengego area.
Over 20 people were killed in clashes between the Nuer and Anuak communities in Gambela Regional State over 28-30 January.
OLA forces attacked government soldiers in Arada 25 in Oda Bultum district, West Hararghe Zone, killing five soldiers and wounding another three. Military material was also captured.
Students protested to demand payment of scholarships and were dispersed by police.
Students protested to demand payment of scholarships and were dispersed by police, who reportedly used violence and teargas, causing injuries.
A priest was murdered by Fulani Cattle herders in the Asante region.
Thousands of workers in Ghana are hitting the streets in Accra to protest the recent hikes in petroleum products and utility tariffs. The TUC was active in the protest.
Nationwide protests, under the banner of the TUC, took place in Aflao.
Nationwide protests, under the banner of the TUC, took place in Cape Coast.
Protesters aligned to the Trades Union Congress took to the streets in Ho, as part of nationwide demonstrations.
Workers of 13 unions of the Trades Union Congress (TUC) in the Koforidua Municipality  hit the streets in support of the nationwide demonstration declared by the TUC
Hundreds of workers responded to the call by the leadership of organized labour to hit the streets in protest in Kumasi. The TUC has been at the forefront of these nationwide protest.
Demonstrations, led by the TUC and public servants, took place in Nsawan as part of nationwide protest action.
More than 500 members of the Organised Labour (TUC) in the Western Region took part in a demonstration in the Sekondi-Takoradi Metropolis.
Hundreds of workers, under the banner of the TUC, poured out on to the streets of Sunyani to register their discontent with the recent increases in utility tariffs and prices of petroleum products.
Nationwide protests, under the banner of the TUC, took place in Tamale.
Nationwide protests, under the banner of the TUC, took place in Tema.
About 150 members of Organised Labour in the Upper West Region have participated in a peaceful demonstration in Wa to protest against the recent tariff increases and fuel price hikes.

Clashes between the Jafoak and Jamong Families over chieftancy in Bunkpurugu led to the killing of three persons and burning of more than 30 houses. One person was arrested in connection with the clashes.

ACTOR1: UFDG: Union of Democratic Forces of Guinea
ACTOR2: UFDG: Union of Democratic Forces of Guinea
NOTES: Clashes between security guards of Cellou Dalein Diallo and Bah Oury at the Union des Forces Démocratiques de Guinée (UFDG) headquarters.
Communal clashes related to a land conflict between Denan village and Koideguezon village left 7 injured in the Toulepleu department.
High school students went on a two day strike to protest fees.
Secondary school teachers went on a five day strike to protest poor facilities.
Minors protested water shortage.

After protesting the day before, three activists were arrested for "disturbing public order". Protesters "besieged" the police station where they were being held, demanding their release. All three were released the following day.
Angry at the arrest of protest leaders the day before, protesters blocked roads and were dispersed by police using tear gas.

Suspected al Shabaab ambushed a police convoy in Lamu on the afternoon of 01/01, injuring security officials and setting a police truck on fire. There was a fierce gun battle at the scene preceded by an explosion. Shortly after the attack police forces in the area launched a large security operation.

Five men were admitted to hospital after they were attacked by a gang of armed men in Silaloni, Samburu Sub-County, in Kwale. The camel keepers were attacked by men armed with pangas, bows and arrows as well as other crude weapons on the morning of 02/01. The reason for attack is not known.
Hundreds of women on 10/01 protested in Mombasa against  a Senator who publically criticised President Uhuru Kenyatta. The protesters demanded the Senator apologise.
The Anti-Terrorism Police Unit on [20 January] morning killed four al Shabaab after a shootout in Kwachocha, Malindi.
Laikipia University students riot following a released report recommending the closure of their school. Police fired tear gas and made several arrests.

Three people were killed while another one was seriously injured after morans from two communities clashed over land in Leparua on the Isiolo-Laikipia border. The identity of the actors are not known.
Six police (or seven - Shabelle Media Network) officers are killed when their vehicle struck an IED in Lamu, suspected al Shabaab responsible.
More than 400 residents of Mpeketoni in Lamu County protested over increased insecurity and frequent attacks by Al-Shabaab militia which have been experienced in the region in the recent past.
A gang on the night of 31/01 raided Meru Governor Peter Munya's home and vandalised one of his official security cars. The governor was away, and was not harmed.
Suspected Tugen militia attack and kill a Njemp (Ilchamus) man in Olesampurmpur Village in Baringo 31/01.
Al Shabaab attacks Pandanguo village, targeting the homes of Christians. Al Shabaab claimed "many" killed, though more reliable reports indicate three dead, plus injuries.
About one hundred former Ebola workers yesterday staged a peaceful demonstration in front of the Ministry of Health in Monrovia.
Protesters stormed a court last Thursday in protest. However, no one was physically attacked and no property damaged during the hours-long protest

ACTOR2: Military Forces of Liberia (2005-) Presidential Guard
NOTES: Clashes took place between the Liberian National Police and the Executive Protection Service (the official title of the Presidential Guard) after a police vehicle intrudes into the Presidential Convoy. The clash results in a few security personnel going to hospital with minor injuries.
Over 400 residents of Weala gathered at the  offices of a Chinese firm in a peaceful protest demanding reparation for the demolition of their homes.

Protesting University of Liberia students from opposing campus-based parties booed and threw stones at House Speaker Alex Tyler who had come to engage with students on the main campus, disbursing the crowd

ACTOR2: BRSC: Shura Council of Benghazi Revolutionaries
NOTES: Eight Libyan soldiers were killed and at least 10 others injured in clashes with a coalition of Islamist militias in Libya's eastern city of Benghazi. The clashes erupted in the western Al-Hawari district on Friday [1 January] night between forces loyal to the Commander-in-Chief of the Libyan army Khalifah Haftar and fighters of the Benghazi Revolutionaries Shura Council.

LNA-allied fighters (Tribes Army) launched a surprise attack on the pro-GNC Sabratha Military Council militias in the towns of al-Tawila and al-Shabika, south of Sabratha. However, Sabratha Military Council forces appear to have repelled the attacks.

ADMIN1: Tajura wa an Nawahi al Arba
NOTES: Unidentified gunmen assassinated a local militia commander in Tajoura, Abdul Basset Shar. Local militia forces increased security after the assassination of Shar, who allegedly played a role in the arrest and execution of the now defunct LNA-allied Battalion 101s commander, Abdullah Sassi.
A potential ceasefire in Ajdabiya was aborted before negotiations as unknown militants attacked the mediators by shooting at them.
It was reported that a Libyana mobile telecommunications relay station near Ajdabiya was blown up by Islamic State militants.

SOURCE: Agence France Presse; Associated Press International; Xinhua General News Service; Al-Arabiya TV; Libya Herald
NOTES: Islamic State militants carried out a suicide car bomb attack on a military checkpoint at the entrance to the town of Al-Sidra. Violent clashes erupted afterwards with the Petroleum Facilities Guards (PFG), a local militia group loyal to the Libyan army that control the majority of Libya's oil fields. Six of their fighters were killed in Monday's attacks, along with five IS fighters in the coastal port town of Sidra.
Operation Dawn reportedly conducted air strikes on Islamic State militiant positions between Al-Sidra and Ben Jawad, an air force colonel in Misrata said.
The Islamic State (IS) group took control of Ben Jawad town, 150 kilometres (90 miles) east of Sirte.

SOURCE: Agence France Presse; Associated Press International; Xinhua General News Service; Al-Arabiya TV
NOTES: Islamic State militants launched an attack on the town of Ras Lanouf via the south but did not manage to enter.

An Operation Dignity warplane conducted a raid against Ansar positions in Sidi Faraj near Bouatni. It later crashed, but it was claimed the hydraulic system caught fire which then which then caused a rocket to explode, rather than being shot down from the ground.

For the second day running, IS militants attacked oil facilities in an area 20 kilometres (12 miles) southwest of Al-Sidra, along Libya's northern coast. Clashes were reported with oil facility guards backed by the air force. The fighting is happening in an area 20 kilometres (12 miles) southwest of Al-Sidra. Seven deaths reported.

The oil installations guard force had to fight intermittent battles with Islamic State fighters as they mopped the battle ground on 6 January. The clashes in which light arms were used took place in Wadi Kehaila near the oil terminals in the east of the country.
There are reports that Ibrahim Jadhran and his Petroleum Facilities Guards (PFG) units pursued Islamic State militants and was involved in fighting just east of Ben Jawad.

The mayor of Gharyan, south of Tripoli, was shot at on 7 January in what appears to have been an assassination attempt. Yousif Budeiri took a bullet in the leg while outside the local security headquarters. He was taken to the local hospital for treatment.

Amid rising anger across Libya at the Zliten suicide attack, demonstrators in Misrata broke into the local bureau of Naaba TV, accusing it of sympathising with the so-called Islamic State and demanding that it close.
An Islamic State bomber drove an explosives-packed car into a checkpoint at the entrance to the town of Ras Lanouf. group, killing six people, including a baby.

SOURCE: Agence France Presse; Al-Jazeera TV; Associated Press International
NOTES: Between 50-55 people were killed after the Islamic State launched a suicide bomb attack on the the Al-Jahfal camp - a police training academy in Zliten (170 km east of Tripoli). Associated Press reported 60 casualties. The group calling itself the IS Barqa Province said the attack was carried out by one of their fighters, who detonated his explosive-laden truck among the Libyan border police at the base.

Security forces disarmed a vehicle-borne improvised explosive device (VBIED) in front of the College of Sciences at Marqub University in Khoms. Additional reporting indicates unidentified militants briefly broke into the university and threatened to blow it up, before surrounding a police station in the al-Khamis Market in Khoms.

SOURCE: Libya Herald; Libya Observer; Libya TV 24
NOTES: An ambulance full of explosives was safely dealt with in Misrata on 8 January after security forces prevented it from heading to its target. The ambulance was detected and was given chase, forced into less built-up areas. The driver refused to stop and either self-detonated his explosives or it exploded as a result of shots fired at it from the pursuing Misratan security forces. The ambulance was totally destroyed but it caused no real damage to surrounding property and no one was reported injured.

ADMIN1: Tajura wa an Nawahi al Arba
NOTES: Calls for Naaba and Tabasah TV stations to close were heard in protests over the Zliten attack in Tripolis Algeria Square. They are both accused of sympathising with Islamic State.

Thirty people from the city of Sabratha were kidnapped in nearby Surman on Friday connected to the Shershary children kidnapping. The kidnapping was in revenge for the arrest of a kidnapping and extortion cell in the western region.
Misrata's Ad Dafniya checkpoint was closed by angry protesters who rejected the visit of the Prime Minister of UN-imposed government Fayaz Sirraj and some members of the presidency council.

At Misrata Airport under tightening security measures, protesters gathered outside the airport to denounce the visit of the Prime Minister of UN-imposed government Fayaz Sirraj and some members of the presidency council who were set to visit Zliten, which they described as political propaganda.

Armed protesters started to gather and blocked the entrances to Zliten in anger at a delegation of the Prime Minister of UN-imposed government Fayaz Sirraj and some members of the presidency council. As the delegation left, Sirraj's motorcade came under heavy fire and diverted to Zliten municipal council for safety. There, other protesters besieged the municipal building and clashed with Sirraj's bodyguards, mainly from Misrata's Al-Halboos Brigade.

SOURCE: Libya Herald; Al-Wasat; Afrigate; Libya Observer
NOTES: A standoff has been ongoing all today with exchange of gunfire at a house believed to be where three Sabratha Shershary kidnapped children are being held in the Beach club area of Surman. The operation is a joint action by Sabratha and Surman authorities. Members of the Sharshara tribe and elements known as the Tiger militia clashed with the Joint Force in Surman following a kidnapping incident with at least 2 casualties among the joint forces.

Misratan forces shoot at an ambulance full of explosives. The ambulance detonated, either due to the shots fired or due to the driver triggering the explosives. The ambulance was believed to have been heading towards the city's airport and the visiting party of Fayiz al-Sarraj, prime minister designate of the GNA [Government of National Accord].

Unidentified forces fired at least four rockets at two camps for internally displaced people in Benghazi on January 9, 2016. Three rockets struck the Red Crescent Camp (also known as the Sports City Camp), killing three civilians and wounding seven others, including two children. One of the witnesses said that the rockets originated from the al-Qwarsha area, which is controlled by the Islamist militias. Human Rights Watch could not confirm the origin of the rocket strikes.

ADMIN1: Tajura wa an Nawahi al Arba
NOTES: A vehicle-borne improvised explosive device (VBIED) exploded on Omar al-Mukhtar Street in downtown Tripoli, causing damage to surrounding shops but no casualties. No group has claimed responsibility, but the attack was likely carried out by IS.

More than 14 people were killed and 5 injured in clashes between Tabu and Tuareg groups since confrontations erupted in Ubari, Sunday 10 January, according to Buhena. Fatalities divided between 3 events(5 recorded on 11 and 12 January; 4 fatalities recorded on 10 January.
On 10 January, unidentified warplanes attacked a Islamic State militant convoy in Sirte, supposedly inflicting heavy casualties.

The LNA-allied 21 Border Guards Battalion seized the al-Qanaan area, southeast of Ajdabiya near the 18 Gate, from IS and Ajdabiya Shura Council (ASC) forces. One 21 Border Guard fighter was killed in the fighting, and a number wounded. The ASC declared the region a military zone, but has not admitted the loss of the district.
Warplanes of the Air Force bombed the Ajdabiya Shura Council rebels south of the city of Ajdabiya.

SOURCE: Agence France Presse; Jamahiriya News Agency (JANA)
NOTES: Libyan Oil Installation Guards repelled a maritime assault by the Islamic State group on Zueitina oil terminal in the north of the country on 10 January. They opened fire and hit one of the boats. The other two made off but returned a short while later to tow the vessel which had been hit.

More than 14 people were killed and 5 injured in clashes between Tabu and Tuareg groups since confrontations erupted in Ubari, Sunday 10 January, according to Buhena. Fatalities divided between 3 events (5 recorded on 11 and 12 January; 4 fatalities recorded on 10 January.
According to the head of Saiqas Investigation Unit, three non-combatants were wounded, one seriously, when a shell exploded in Hadaiq.
Unconfirmed reports indicate IS executed five Libyan youths, allegedly former members of the security forces, in a public square in Ben Jawad, east of Sirte.
IS fighters kidnapped six Egyptian nationals after stopping their bus on the road south of Abu Qarin and executed the bus driver as the group traveled from Khoms.
Members of 204 Brigade were involved in clashes with militants in the citys Belawn district; six missiles are reported to have landed there.

ACTOR1: Military Forces of Libya (2014-) Special Forces
NOTES: The Counter Crime Agencys headquarters in Benghazis Hadaiq district came under attack as gunmen tried to free a man detained there arrested last week. The 21 Saiqa Brigade responded. The Libya Observer reported that the attackers were Sahawat "Awakening" groups affiliated with Khalifa Haftar's forces.

A shooting occurred outside the Mellitah compound, the oil terminal of ENI [Italy's National Hydrocarbons Body] in Libya. The attack,which lasted a few minutes, targeted a checkpoint of the Misrata militiamen who are entrusted with protecting the terminal. The facilitys guards repelled the assault with the assistance of reinforcements from Sabrathas Um al-Gharib Brigade.
One Islamic State commander was killed on 12 January in Sirte by a sniper inside the city.

Renewed clashes in Obari have left a total of 14 people dead and at least seven injured including a young child. The latest violence, which the news agency LANA reported involved bombardments by medium and heavy weapons, comes after a few days of uneasy peace. On Tuesday, the town's castle was damanged. Fatalities divided between 3 events (5 recorded on 11 and 12 January; 4 fatalities recorded on 10 January.
Air raids were reported in Leithi.

On 12 January, The 21st Border Guard Battalion seized the 60 Gate area, south of Ajdabiya on the Jalu Road, from the Ajdabiya Revolutionaries Shura Council (ARSC). At least two ARSC fighters were killed, and at least one technical was captured.

Commander of the Ajdabiya Border Guards, Bashir Abu Dhafira, announced the formation of a joint operations room with the Petroleum Facilities Guard (PFG) forces and (likely Libya Dawn) forces in the west and south of the country to liberate Sirte from IS control.
IS has claimed that it was responsible the destruction of a section of the oil pipeline which was bombed near Maradah and the kidnapping of six locals.

Two mystery warplanes launched a night raid against Islamic State positions in Sirte, targeting buildings on the edge of the town, in the Al-Sabiha and Dahira districts. One site that was hit is said to have been a weapons store.

IS fighters kidnapped 5 PFG members from near the Marada Oil Field. On 16 JAN an unofficial IS statement claimed credit for the raid and identified the attack as part of the ongoing al-Qahtani Campaign.

SOURCE: Libya Herald; Libya Security Monitor; Al-Wasat
NOTES: There are unconfirmed reports that Islamic State militants are holding more than 150 men in a compound in Nufaliya, 140 kilometres east of Sirte. Their offence has been that they either refused to join the fighters or declare their allegiance to IS.
The LNA announced that it had taken control of the 18 and 60 Gates and 100 Point on the road south of Ajdabiya city.

LNA-allied local fighters clashed with Ajdabiya Revolutionaries Shura Council (ARSC) forces in the vicinity of the the Sharouq Mosque in the southwest of the Industrial Neighborhood of Ajdabiya. LNA fighters also stormed the farm of ASC member Breik al-Masriya south of the 7 October Neighborhood, seizing aircraft bombs and other weaponry and killing two ASC fighters and wounding others.

4 people were killed and 12 others were injured in fresh clashes between Tabu and Tuareg tribes in Ubari on 15 January, in violation of Doha ceasefire agreement signed between both tribes in November.

ALLY_ACTOR_2: BRSC: Shura Council of Benghazi Revolutionaries
NOTES: The Libyan National Army shot down a camera-mounted miniature drone aircraft which it claimed was being used by Ansar Al-Sharia to survey its positions near Garyounis. At the same time the air force targeted Ansar positions in Gwarsha and at Mreisa port.

ALLY_ACTOR_2: BRSC: Shura Council of Benghazi Revolutionaries
NOTES: In Buhdeima district of Benghazi on 15 January, a young girl was reported killed in a random rocket attack in on-going clashes between the Libya National Army and the BRSC.

ALLY_ACTOR_2: BRSC: Shura Council of Benghazi Revolutionaries
NOTES: The Libyan Air Force targeted Ansar positions in Gwarsha and at Mreisa port.

ALLY_ACTOR_2: BRSC: Shura Council of Benghazi Revolutionaries
NOTES: The Libyan Air Force targeted Ansar al-Sharia positions in Gwarsha and at Mreisa port.

ALLY_ACTOR_2: BRSC: Shura Council of Benghazi Revolutionaries
NOTES: A number of missiles landed in Sidi Yunis district, with no reports of casualties.

ACTOR2: BRSC: Shura Council of Benghazi Revolutionaries
NOTES: A senior commander of the Benghazi Shura Council was killed in clashes against renegade Gen. Khalifa Haftar's forces on 16 January.

ACTOR2: BRSC: Shura Council of Benghazi Revolutionaries
NOTES: Missile fire was reported in Leithi district of Benghazi, although again no one is said to have been hurt.

ACTOR2: BRSC: Shura Council of Benghazi Revolutionaries
NOTES: Intermittent explosions were reported in Ard Zwawa district of Benghazi. A number of buildings as well as vehicles were said to have been hit, but there are no reports of any casualties. There was also missile fire in Leithi, although again no one is said to have been hurt.
A demonstration in support of the Libyan-Libyan dialogue took place in the center of Misratah city.

The Libyan navy says it has detained 14 suspected militants found on board a Panamanian-flagged vessel stopped and boarded within territorial waters off Ras Hilal. 12 Syrians and two Indians were arrested on the ship which they named as the Abella.

IS executed two young men in Sirte whom it accused of being Libya Dawn spies. The murders were carried out in the usual fashion, with the victims being crucified on the frame of a former advertising hoarding in the middle of a roundabout in the town.
Unidentified attackers threw an improvised explosive device (IED) at an IS patrol near the Insurance Building in Sirte.
IS fighters executed three unidentified individuals and displayed their bodies outside of Ben Jawad, in order to intimidate the local citizens.
Local fighters in Surman clashed with suspected IS militants southwest of the city. The militants attacked a farm in Um Hashan, but failed to take control of the territory.

The Director of the passport authority Gharyan branch was kidnapped on 17 January in mysterious circumstances. The man disappeared in Al Regai'at on Kassarat highway on his way back to Gharyan from Tripoli.

ACTOR2: BRSC: Shura Council of Benghazi Revolutionaries
NOTES: LNA forces took control of the Flour Factory in the Sidi Faraj area of Benghazi. The factory is located near the border of the Buatni neighborhood and Sidi Faraj, a highly contested region.

ACTOR1: Military Forces of Libya (2014-) Special Forces
NOTES: Al-Saiqa Special Forces repelled a dawn attack on the Chocolate Factory in Laithi district of Benghazi by suspected IS forces.

Two IS militants were killed on Monday by fighters of Derna Shura Council, after they attempted to infiltrate into the city from Al-Fatayah mountains. The two militants were wearing women's full-face veils and explosive belts. The Shura Council said the two were planning to carry out a suicide attack inside Derna.
Five Grad missiles were fired from Leithi and landed near Benina Airport causing minor damage but no injuries.

Angry protesters went to the streets of Al-Bayda on 19 January to denounce the deteriorating living conditions in the city. The protesters accused the Al-Thani government of being behind all the problems in the city including lack of cash and blackouts. Protesters burned tyres outside the National Commercial Bank due to lack of cash.
An armed group stormed the Libyan Constitution Drafting Assembly headquarters in the eastern city of Al-Bayda on Tuesday and ordered the staff to leave.

ADMIN1: Tajura wa an Nawahi al Arba
NOTES: A young Tripoli imam was abducted by unknown gunmen as he headed from from Ishaa prayers at his mosque in Tripoli.

Fighting in Benghazi intensified as the army repelled one assault by IS and then appeared to make ground in Sabri and Suq Al-Hud. Four soldiers were seriously injured in fighting while the army claimed that it had killed at least three IS fighters who had been attacking a base in the chocolate factory.
An alleged IS senior commander Abu Mohamed al-Dernawi, was found dead with a gunshot wound in the head near Hawara, an IS controlled town 70km from Sirte.
IS militants fired a series of mortars and shells which hit a block of flats killing a 49 year old woman in Benghazi.

Representatives from the mountain towns of Zintan and Kikla signed a peace agreement to end conflict. Under the deal, Zintani forces will withdraw from the town which will now be occupied by neutral forces from Zawiya and Motrad. Both sides also agreed to exchange prisoners and avoid any actions that might lead to further conflict.

SOURCE: Agence France Presse; Associated Press International; Libya Observer
NOTES: Oil facilities in northern Libya were set ablaze on 21 January as the Islamic State group launched fresh attacks to seize key export terminals. Fighting was reported between Petroleum Facilities Guards (PFG) and Islamic State militants as they attacked oil terminals in Ras Lanuf by firing rockets. No reports of casualties.

Fighting broke out in the town of Tarhouna, 80 kilometres south east of Tripoli between the pro-Islamist Al-Kanni brigade and local families opposed to it from the Naja'a tribe. Three people are said to have been killed and the Kanni brigade to have blown up a number of homes of their opponents.
LNA aircraft conducted air strikes on the Industrial Neighborhood of Ajdabiya.

Fighting between LNA-allied 21st Border Guards Battalion and local fighters against Ajadbiya Revolutionaries Shura Council (ARSC) forces continued in the vicinity of Istanbul Street in Ajdabiya. Heavy losses were reported during the clashes.

In Benghazi, on 22 January, some couple of hundred demonstrators voiced their support for Hafter in Kish Square, and denounced Al-Hejazi, the spokesman of the leader of the Libyan army who recently defected after accusing Haftar of corruption.

The Libyan Air Force said that it carried out air strikes against IS vehicles in Ben Jawad, the town seized by the militants last week and used as a jumping-off point for the attacks on Sidra and Ras Lanuf. Air Force spokesman Nasser Al-Hassi said that the raids by Mig-21s had caused the militants heavy losses in both lives and material.

ACTOR1: Military Forces of the United Kingdom
ALLY_ACTOR_1: Military Forces of the United States
NOTES: Military forces from Britain, US and Russia arrived in Libya to support the new UN-backed government, London-based Asharq Al-Awsat newspaper reported on Saturday, adding a French one is to follow soon. Dozens of soldiers and officers landed at Jamal Abdel Nasser military base south of Tobruk.
3 Libyans were killed by Islamic State (IS) militants in Noufliyah.
An IS commander, Abdullah Hamad Al-Ansari, was killed by a sharpshooter on 23 January as he left a mosque in Sirte. Ansari was rushed to hospital where he died.
On 25 January, the Ajdabiya Shura Council claimed to have retaken the 18 Gate from the LNA 21 Border Guards. The gate, southeast of the city, was secured by the LNA on 10 JAN.

A senior member of the Misratan 3rd Force, was abducted in al-Shati in South Libya. A convoy of vehicles from Misrata headed south in response. Unconfirmed reports indicate that the Ben Nayal tribe militias (seen as pro-Gaddafi) were involved in the kidnapping. No mention of a battle.

ADMIN1: Tajura wa an Nawahi al Arba
NOTES: A man in police custody is suspected of trying to plant a bomb outside the Sudanese Embassy in the Gargaresh district of Tripoli. The suspect was picked up by the Abu Sleem police after a bomb alleged to contain 200 grammes of TNT was discovered at the embassy. The device failed to detonate. It is unclear where the bomb was discovered or how the suspect was arrested.
A civilian from Kikla was injured due to a land mine explosion in the city center. The bomb was likely planted by the Zintani armed groups during the last fight in the city.

Islamic State militants murdered three of the six men kidnapped when the they launched an attack on Petroleum Facilities Guards (PFG) on 14 January near Maradah earlier this month. The location and date of the execution was not reported.
The Libyan National Army air force conducted airstrikes on Bouatni district against IS forces.
The Petroleum Facilities Guards (PFG) are reported to have been involved in fighting around Ben Jawad. The source did not specify the second actor involved in the clashes.

ADMIN1: Tajura wa an Nawahi al Arba
NOTES: Fierce clashes were reported in the south Tripoli suburb of Qasr Ben Gashir between Misratan forces and fighters belonging to Salah Marghanis brigade. As many as 10  people were killed. 5 fatalities recorded on 1 February.

Islamic State militants are being blamed for the bombing of pipelines leading to the export terminal at Zuetina, north of Ajdabiya on 31 January. The attack which caused a fire, happened some 75 kilometres south of the terminal.
A firefight between dahalo and gendarmes left one soldier dead.
100 protesters total between Ambatomena and Ambohijatovo demonstrated to demand the return of the Scattered Islands. Larger number of security forces used tear gas to disperse the small crowds.
100 protesters total between Ambatomena and Ambohijatovo demonstrated to demand the return of the Scattered Islands. Larger number of security forces used tear gas to disperse the small crowds.
In front of City Hall, merchants protested bans on street markets. Police dispered them and one was assaulted by protesters.
Unidentified attackers set fire to the JIRAMA regional offices, perhaps using a molotov cocktail.
Battle between Dahalo and gendarmes left one gendarme dead.
Firefight between about 60 Dahalo and gendarmes left several injured.
Dahalo hunmen killed 2 people while stealing cattle. At least one victim was decapitated.
Vigilante mob beat to death a man who had just been released from prison.
Rioters destroyed church property and set fire to vehicles after hearing a rumour that a pastor had turned into a snake. Police fired tear gas.
Kasungu residents riot and block roads protesting against sale of maize.
Mtakataka residents riot and block roads protesting against sale of maize.
Kasungu residents riot and block roads for second day protesting against sale of maize.
Mtakataka residents riot and block roads for second day protesting against sale of maize.
Mob killed 4 in Chimbalanga who they suspected of using witchcraft to kill a young woman  - the woman was killed by lightning strike.
Vendors protest in Dzenza over placement of stalls.

ACTOR1: AQIM: Al Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb
NOTES: Gunmen abducted a Swiss woman, Beatrice Stockly, from her home for the second time. AQIM later claimed responsibility.

SOURCE: Agence France Presse - English; Xinhua News Agency - French
NOTES: Two soldiers killed when assailants attacked the aid convoy they were escorting about 11 km from Goundam. One attacker arrested and two killed.
Security guard from the Water and Forests Agency killed when Islamists attacked a market.
Three gendarmes killed in an ambush by Islamist militants.
Gunmen attacked the residence of the Public Prosecutor in Gao; a guard returned fire, killing one.

SOURCE: Agence France Presse - English; Associated Press International
NOTES: Soldier killed in an ambush just east of Timbuktu.

SOURCE: Agence France Presse - English; Associated Press International
NOTES: Three soldiers died and two seriously injured when their vehicle hit an explosive device.
30 Islamist prisoners launched a hunger strike to denounce punitive measures in the jail.
Families of Salafi prisoners protested outside the jail.
Three migrants drowned and about 20 were hospitalized when hundreds tried to cross into Ceuta. Some injuries may have been caused by security forces as 250 were arrested.

SOURCE: Morocco World News; Human Rights Watch
NOTES: Between 800 and 2,000 teacher trainees marched in Casablanca to protest several policies and police used "excessive force" to disperse them. Around 40 were injured.

SOURCE: Morocco World News; Human Rights Watch
NOTES: Teacher trainees held sit-ins as part of a national movement against reduced stipends and other employment practices.

SOURCE: Morocco World News; Human Rights Watch
NOTES: Teacher trainees were beaten by police while protesting. Around 100 were injured in Inezgane, where the level of violence was especially high.

SOURCE: Morocco World News; Human Rights Watch
NOTES: Teacher trainees held sit-ins and were met with "extreme violence" from the police. Around 20 were injured.

SOURCE: Morocco World News; Human Rights Watch
NOTES: Teacher trainees held sit-ins as part of a national movement against reduced stipends and other employment practices.

SOURCE: Morocco World News; Human Rights Watch
NOTES: Teacher trainees were beaten by police while protesting. Around 8 were injured.

Protesters from a wide range of groups marched in general opposition to the political system.

ALLY_ACTOR_1: UGTM: General Union of Moroccan Workers
SOURCE: La Nouvelle Tribune; Agence France Presse
NOTES: Nearly 2,000 protesters led by four main unions held a sit-in in front of Parliament and threatened a general strike to protest various policies including pension reform.
After police beat protesters on Jan 7th, teacher trainees continue to protest regularly in Inezgane. No further violence reported.
Amazigh activitists protested in front of PJD headquarters in response to an "anti-Amazigh" statement by the Prime Minister.

"Scores" of protesters and supporters of the Feb 20 Movement protested in front of parliament, denouncing ministers' retirement benefits. Pro-government protesters attempted to rush the Feb 20 Movement protesters, but police prevented them from clashing.
Authorities "intervened brutally" to disperse a demonstration by Saharawi activists, causing several injuries.
Thousands marched along with teacher trainees in opposition to decrees by the Ministry of Education.
Anti-Polisario protesters marched and burned Polisario flags while chanting anti-Algeria slogans after claims that Polisario attacked Amazigh people on Moroccan university campuses.
Local media reported a clash between government troops and Renamo in Tete on December 31, in which six houses were burnt down.

Unidentified armed men attempted to murder Manuel Bissopo, the general secretary of the country's main opposition party Renamo in Beira. The assailants shot at the car he was driving, killing his bodyguard, and seriously injuring Bissopo.

Residents of the town Palmeiras, 70km from Maputo, demonstrated against the alleged complicity of the police with criminals in the town on 22 January. They threw up barricades of burning tyres on the main north-south highway. The local police called for reinforcements from Maputo, and in the ensuing clashes one protester was shot dead.

Renamo gunmen attacked a position of the Mozambique army at the village of Zero, in Morrumbala district, in the central province of Zambezia. Three members of the police unit to protect natural resources were severely injured in the clash.
Police discover and detonate an anti-tank mine at Onekaku village near Oshigambo.
TransNamib employees protest for equal treatment.
Clashes between 'struggle kids' rioters and an armed white farmer. Rioters threw rocks at farm and then chopped farmer with a machete. Farmer fired back with bullets. 4 rioters injured.

ACTOR2: Police Forces of Namibia (2005-) Special Reserve Force
NOTES: Mob of struggle kids gather in Windhoek at Brakwater settlement, where 400 struggle kids were relocated to the Ndilimani Cultural Troupe Farm on Dec 12. Rioters blocked roads and attacked residents with pangas. Special Reserve Forces fired tear gas and rubber bullets.
Mob of struggle kids gather in Windhoek at Brakwater settlement, attacked residents with panga knives.
Child injured playing with a hand grenade in Kehemu near Rundu.

ACTOR2: Police Forces of Namibia (2005-) Special Reserve Force
NOTES: Struggle kids block roads near Brakwater settlement. Special Reserve Forces fired tear gas and rubber bullets.
Students protest against increased registration fees.
Explosive device found in Eros.
Students protest registration fees.
Students in Ongwediva demonstrated against registration fees.

NOTES: Specialist physicians went on a ten day strike to demand salary and certification changes.
At least six soldiers were killed and five wounded when their vehicle hit an explosive device likely planted by Boko Haram.
Public media workers went on a 48 hour strike to demand better working conditions and increased pay.

Suspected Fulani gunmen attacked two settlements in Udeni Ruwa District, Nasarawa Local Government Area of Nararawa state killing between 12 and 13 people. The effected villages are Okpaya, were five were reported dead and Udeni, where eight were believed dead.

The ad hoc staff of the Independent National Electoral Commission protest in Lokoja on 04/01 over unpaid salaries.
