More than 100 people in Wamulongo village in Mpungwe Sub County in Mayuge district are out in the cold after their houses were set ablaze by angry residents to avenge the killing of 38-year old Zedekiya Mwesigwa
Police used tear gas to disperse cyclists who were protesting the payment of annual fees for their operations in Lira municipality.
Two suspected Turkana warriors have died in a gunfire exchange with Uganda People's Defense Forces in Kaabong district.
Police have used teargas and sticks to disperse rioting residents in Kasiiso trading center in Butuntumula Sub County in Luweero district.

Ali Lubuuka Golooba, a journalist with Buddu FM in Masaka is nursing injuries he sustained in an attack by suspected body guards of Muhammad Muyanja Mbabaali, the Bukoto South NRM parliamentary candidate in Lwengo district.
A demonstration allegadly took place by unemployed youth on 12th January in Kampala.
A reporter was reportedly assaulted by a Ugandan police officer in Kampala while covering a demonstration by a group of unemployed youth.
NRM supporters, rooting for two different candidates, were involved in skirmishes. Several people were injured when supporters moved in to prevent his vehicle from being set ablaze.

ACTOR1: FDLR: Democratic Forces for the Liberation of Rwanda
NOTES: FDLR rebels have allegedly kidnapped five Ugandans for ransom in the course of the month of January. Location of kidnapping unknown.

A resident of a village in Rugando sub-county claims that NRM supporters broke into resident's houses and assaulted them. According to Francis, two of his daughters sustained injuries on the head and legs and are currently admitted at Bugamba Health Center IV.
More than 200 unemployed youths stormed the offices of the firm, Sinohydro, the Chinese company building the 600MW Karuma power dam, expressing their plight of being unemployed.
Six residents of Ruhinda County in Mitooma district are nursing injuries following violent clashes involving supporters of rival candidates of the ruling NRM party.

Hundreds of residents of Bulawula and Nakaseta villages decided to set up bonfires and raise barricades to protest against the poor state of the Luweero-Nakaseke road. Anti-riot police fired teargas to break up the demonstration.
Police fired tear gas in Igorora, Ibanda district, to disperse a crowd that had gathered after the official campaign deadline of 6pm and asked FDC presidential candidate Besigye to "greet" them

SOURCE: Associated Press International; Uganda Radio Network
NOTES: Military forces arrested former military general Sejusa on 31 January in Kampala, ahead of presidential elections. He was remanded to Luzira prison on 2 February and charged with insubordination, participating in political party activities and being absent without leave.

SOURCE: The Post; Zambia Reports; Times of Zambia
NOTES: Kafue residents riot and burn Mthendere and Lumumba police posts after a police vehicle hit a vendor in the market.  One rioter shot dead by stray bullets. 35 arrested.
Chimwemwe rioters beat up a policeman suspected of being drunk while on patrol.  Cop threw tear gas.
Policeman shot a man in the leg for breaking a curfew.

Rioters looted and set fire to a stall in Mansa after a rumour spread that the stall owner had harmed a shoplifting boy.  The rioters then went to the stall owner's home and tore down part of the roof. Police arrested 12.
Lukulu residents rioted at police station after an arrestee injured himself during an escape attempt. Rioters looted and broke locks, setting 27 prisoners free. 3 policemen injured.
Copperbelt University students protested on campus against delayed payments of meal allowances.
Copperbelt University students block roads and destroyed property, burned police tents, in protest of delayed payments of meal allowances. Police fired tear gas.
Copperbelt University students boycott classes after a day of riots over delayed payments of meal allowances.
Chipalo mob attacked and injured a suspected witch with stones and sticks. Police intervened and fired tear gas. 7 arrested.
Drivers in Lusaka on strike.

ALLY_ACTOR_1: UPND: United Party for National Development
NOTES: UPND rioters block traffic and throw stones at cars in Choma. Police threw tear gas. 3 police injured. 21 arrested.

ALLY_ACTOR_1: Students (Zambia); UPND: United Party for National Development
NOTES: Students riot over meal allowances, blocking streets and smashing police vehicles in Kitwe. 25 arrested. UPND cadres were also involved in the riots.
40 touts, vendors and kombi were arrested for roiting and clashing with police in Harare. During the clashes, police were attacked by rioters carrying with stones .

ALLY_ACTOR_1: RTUZ: Rural Teachers' Union of Zimbabwe
NOTES: During a protest led by the Rural Teachers' Union of Zimbabwe (RTUZ), police brutally suppressed the march, arresting and beating some protesters.

ALLY_ACTOR_2: ZANU-PF: Zimbabwe African National Union-Patriotic Front
NOTES: Protesting Omnibus workers, where incidents of stone throwing and destruction of some vehicles occurred, clashed with police and ZANU-PF members in Chitungwiza.
A Journalist was assaulted by police forces during clashes in Chitungwiza.
Operations at a diamond mining company in Chiadzwa were halted by villagers protesting against the alleged failure to exhume the bodies of their relatives currently located within mining fields.

ACTOR2: MDC-T: Movement for Democratic Change (Tsvangirai Faction)
NOTES: Mabvuku legislator James Maridadi (MDC-T) was arrested at Beitbridge Border Post for video-filming Zimbabwe Revenue Authority (Zimra) officials without authority and crossing the port without valid travel documents.

ACTOR1: ZANU-PF: Zimbabwe African National Union-Patriotic Front
NOTES: 12 suspected Zanu-PF activists physically attacked members of the Zimbabwe Republic Police, leaving one of them seriously injured in Chitungwiza.
Touts and vendors took to the streets in Chitungwiza when they paraded a coffin of a tout who was fatally hit by a kombi fleeing from municipal police officers in Harare.

ALLY_ACTOR_1: MDC-T: Movement for Democratic Change (Tsvangirai Faction)
NOTES: At least 100 MDC-T supporters stormed the Grain Marketing Board (GMB) depot in Mutasa District, protesting against alleged partisan distribution of seed and fertiliser under the Presidential Inputs Scheme.

ALLY_ACTOR_1: ZANU-PF: Zimbabwe African National Union-Patriotic Front
NOTES: Protesters demonstrated in Hatcliffe accusing a ZANU-PF member of failing to protect them from housing cooperatives and land barons who were demanding large sums of money from homeseekers.

ALLY_ACTOR_1: PWG: Progressive Women's Group; MDC: Movement for Democratic Change
NOTES: MDC MP for Bulawayo Metropolitan Jasmine Toffa and other civil society activists were Thursday arrested in Bulawayo while demonstrating against child abuse and rape. The demonstration had been organised by the Progressive Women's Group.

ALLY_ACTOR_2: MDC-T: Movement for Democratic Change (Tsvangirai Faction)
NOTES: Mutasa Central legislator Trevor Saruwaka (MDC-T) has been arrested for allegedly leading a demonstration against the partisan distribution of seed and fertiliser under the Presidential Inputs Scheme.

ALLY_ACTOR_1: ZANU-PF: Zimbabwe African National Union-Patriotic Front
NOTES: Suspected Zanu-PF youths allegedly torched a house belonging to a Transform Zimbabwe (TZ) activist Kudzanai Gondo, who stood and lost in Mbire by-elections in September last year.

ACTOR1: ZANU-PF: Zimbabwe African National Union-Patriotic Front
ALLY_ACTOR_2: MDC-T: Movement for Democratic Change (Tsvangirai Faction)
NOTES: Mbare councillor, Antony Shingadeya (MDC-T), was hospitalised after he was assaulted by suspected Zanu PF supporters, who besieged an opposition meeting in the politically-volatile suburb.

Mutare has been filled with civil protest as demonstrations erupted in the town centre against findings of a recent Government audit which exposed rampant corruption and breakdown of service delivery at the municipality.

ALLY_ACTOR_1: ZANU-PF: Zimbabwe African National Union-Patriotic Front
NOTES: Suspected ZANU-PF supporters reportedly burnt down the house of a People First (PF)member in Murehwa.

ALLY_ACTOR_1: MDC-T: Movement for Democratic Change (Tsvangirai Faction)
ALLY_ACTOR_2: MDC-T: Movement for Democratic Change (Tsvangirai Faction)
NOTES: Chaotic scenes reportedly marred an MDC-T rally held in Bulawayo, resulting in some party members being beaten up for supporting another faction.

Harare Central Hospital security guards assaulted several nurses, aligned to the Zimbabwe Nurses Association, who were demonstrating against chief executive officer Mrs Peggy Zvavamwe's purchasing of a vehicle.
Over 50 residents picketed outside the offices of the Manicaland Provincial Affairs Minister in Mutare.
